	<div class="posts">
	<a name="108006993170910663">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<a href="http://www.acm.org/technews/articles/2004-6/0322m.html#item10">ACM News Service - Cashing in on Virus Infections</a>.&nbsp; This is an interesting blurb about how the business model of antivirus firms has driven out what might be more promising approaches.&nbsp; I agree that the updated, signature-based systems are very convenient, and the subscription model is to the advantage of AV firms.&nbsp; But, because of the constant work on new threat approaches by intruders, I don't see how something lik subscriptions can be avoided.&nbsp; What struck me is the observation that e-mail programs are too feature rich, and made feature-easy rather than safety-easy.&nbsp; I would be willing to revert to plaintext-only e-mail as a way to be more secure from viruses.  It won't help with all spam, but it would also filter out much commercial and porn spam as well.<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#108006993170910663">Tuesday, March 23, 2004</a></span></div>
